ass` correctly retrieves a private lookup. It seems I'm also evaluating if finding a static private method requires specific access. Maybe there are challenges with metadata, reflection, or native image risks, plus the deprecation of certain lookup methods in JDK 21.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing private lookup access**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how `privateLookupIn` returns a lookup object and whether `hasFullPrivilegeAccess` can be false. It seems like `privateLookupIn` creates a lookup with PRIVATE, but not MODULE access, which raises questions about privileges. For using `lookup.findStatic`, this is part of the public MethodHandles API. \\n\\nIf a method isn't invoked, then the closed world might need configuration, and there could be potential issues with dynamic access in native images. I also need to verify whether lookup modes include the private option safely.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting repository tests**\\n\\nI think the repository might be testing how to generate metadata and compare it, although the existing metadata seems minimal. It makes me wonder about the build outputs and whether we have dynamic access coverage. I should look into what’s not covered by the tests, particularly focusing on any active classes that might be overlooked. There’s definitely more to uncover here! Let's see what I can find!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BmitpsVCY8fpZl7fNQGCtY0b|fc_0d3e34a014bf1fa50169f19f9784ec8191b4ee002be377694d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport json\np='tests/src/org.apache.calcite/calcite-core/1.35.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json'\nwith open(p) as f: data=json.load(f)\n# search Compatible\nimport pprint\ns=json.dumps(data)\nprint('len', len(s), 'Compatible' in s)\n# print nearby keys\n\ndef walk(o,path=''):\n    if isinstance(o,dict):\n        if any('Compatible' in str(v) for v in o.values()):\n            print(path, o if len(str(o